---
// /faq/ — Frequently asked questions.
// Single source of truth for Q&A; the homepage Faq.astro component
// surfaces 3–4 highest-objection items as collapsibles and links here
// for full answers. Each Q has an H2 with an id matching the homepage
// link fragments.
//
// Pre-Habr scope: English only. RU and other locale variants are a
// follow-up pass — see marketing/feedback/2026-05-28-pre-habr-peer-chat.md §8.
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import FinalCta from '../../components/FinalCta.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../../components/SiteFooter.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="FAQ — SpecScore"
  description="Honest answers to the questions reviewers actually ask: how SpecScore differs from spec-kit, why a CLI exists alongside skills, what 'Score' means, and where the token-savings numbers come from."
  canonical="https://specscore.md/faq/"
>
  <SiteHeader />

  <main>
    <section class="faq-hero" aria-labelledby="faq-hero-title">
      <div class="faq-hero__inner">
        <h1 id="faq-hero-title" class="faq-hero__headline">
          Questions reviewers actually asked.
        </h1>
        <p class="faq-hero__sub">
          Drawn from pre-launch peer feedback. Each answer is the honest
          one, not the marketing one.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-body section" aria-labelledby="faq-list-title">
      <div class="section-inner">
        <h2 id="faq-list-title" class="sr-only">FAQ list</h2>

        <article class="faq-item">
          <h2 id="vs-spec-kit" class="faq-item__q">
            How is SpecScore different from spec-kit?
          </h2>
          <div class="faq-item__a">
            <p>
              <strong>spec-kit is a methodology — a process for writing specs.</strong>
              SpecScore is a <strong>storage format</strong> for the specs you
              write, plus a CLI for querying and editing them. The two compose:
              spec-kit can produce SpecScore files, and a spec-kit extension that
              writes the SpecScore format is in flight.
            </p>
            <p>
              Pick spec-kit when you need a process. Pick SpecScore when you need
              specs that AI agents can lint, query, and mutate without reading
              every file in the repo. Run both when you want both.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="faq-item">
          <h2 id="vs-superpowers" class="faq-item__q">
            How are SpecStudio Skills different from Superpowers and agent-skills?
          </h2>
          <div class="faq-item__a">
            <p>
              Similar in spirit. All three are skill libraries that guide AI
              agents through ideate → specify → plan → implement. The
              difference is mechanical, not philosophical.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>SpecStudio Skills writes its artifacts in the SpecScore
              format</strong> (a defined Markdown + YAML structure) and
              dispatches the <code>specscore</code> CLI for queries, linting,
              and status changes. Superpowers and agent-skills mostly read and
              write files directly via skill prose.
            </p>
            <p>
              Pick SpecStudio Skills when token consumption matters — the CLI
              returns a structured answer to <em>"all open Features with
              unresolved questions"</em> in one call, where a file-based skill
              reads N documents to answer the same thing.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="faq-item">
          <h2 id="why-cli" class="faq-item__q">
            Why a CLI — can I not just install skills?
          </h2>
          <div class="faq-item__a">
            <p>
              Skills can read and write files. They cannot reliably:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>enforce referential integrity across the spec tree (links resolve, IDs unique, indexes stay in sync);</li>
              <li>return a filtered list of "open Features with unanswered questions" without reading every file;</li>
              <li>mutate the right status field at the right time on every artifact.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              The CLI gives agents one clean call per task — the same way
              <code>jq</code> gives you one clean call to query JSON. Skills
              alone cost more tokens, drift more often, and forget to update
              the index.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="faq-item">
          <h2 id="naming" class="faq-item__q">
            Why is it called "SpecScore" — what does it score?
          </h2>
          <div class="faq-item__a">
            <p>
              "Score" reads two ways, and both are intended.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>Partitura.</strong> A structured score of requirements —
              the way a musical score structures parts, voices, and timing. Open
              a SpecScore tree and you should be able to read it the way a
              conductor reads a score: hierarchy, parts, references, all visible
              at once.
            </p>
            <p>
              <strong>A literal quality grade.</strong> The CLI linter is the
              deterministic score (does the spec structure hold up?). The
              <a href="https://specscore.studio/app/github.com/specscore/specstudio-skills/spec/ideas/manual-review-and-score-commands"><code>/score</code> skill</a>
              is the AI-judged score — an A–F readiness grade per artifact, with
              per-axis feedback for the author. The "Score" half of the name
              becomes a feature the tool produces, not just an aspiration.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="faq-item">
          <h2 id="token-savings" class="faq-item__q">
            Show me the token-savings numbers.
          </h2>
          <div class="faq-item__a">
            <p>
              A measured side-by-side comparison is in flight and will publish
              before the Habr post — same task ("what should I work on next?"),
              run twice: once with a vanilla agent reading docs, once with the
              same agent calling the SpecScore CLI. Token counts and time-to-
              answer for both.
            </p>
            <p>
              Until those numbers land, the claim is structural: an agent asking
              the CLI for open Features and unresolved questions gets a small
              structured response. The same agent without the CLI reads N
              documents — N often in the dozens. The CLI surface is built
              precisely to skip that read fan-out.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <p class="faq-extend">
          More questions, or a sharper version of one of these? Open an issue
          at <a href="https://github.com/specscore/specscore/issues">specscore/specscore</a>;
          this page is the canonical FAQ and grows from real reviewer asks.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <FinalCta />
  <SiteFooter />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .sr-only {
    position: absolute;
    width: 1px; height: 1px;
    padding: 0; margin: -1px;
    overflow: hidden;
    clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
    white-space: nowrap; border: 0;
  }

  .faq-hero {
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-3) var(--space-5);
    background: var(--cream);
  }
  .faq-hero__inner {
    max-width: var(--max-content);
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .faq-hero__headline {
    font-size: var(--fs-hero);
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1.04;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    max-width: 22ch;
  }
  .faq-hero__sub {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    color: var(--mid-ink);
    max-width: 50ch;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .faq-body { background: var(--surface); }

  .faq-item {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    padding: var(--space-4) 0;
    max-width: 70ch;
  }
  .faq-item:last-of-type { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--hairline); }
  .faq-item__q {
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    scroll-margin-top: var(--space-4);
  }
  .faq-item__a p,
  .faq-item__a ul {
    color: var(--mid-ink);
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }
  .faq-item__a ul {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
  }
  .faq-item__a li {
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }
  .faq-item__a a {
    color: var(--ink-blue);
    border-bottom: 1px solid currentColor;
  }
  .faq-item__a code {
    font-family: var(--font-code);
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background: var(--cream-2);
    padding: 0.05em 0.3em;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  .faq-extend {
    margin-top: var(--space-5);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--mid-ink);
    max-width: 60ch;
  }
  .faq-extend a {
    color: var(--ink-blue);
    border-bottom: 1px solid currentColor;
  }
</style>
